                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Sleuths hot on realty scam trail
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Mumbai, Nov. 29: The Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) today said R.R. Nair, the former director and CEO of LIC Housing Finance, had accepted a bribe of Rs 45 lakh to clear loans of three entities  DB Realty, the Mantri group and Entertainment World.        
	This was revealed when eight persons arrested by the agency were produced in a special court here today.         
	The CBI had made the arrests on November 24 in relation to a housing loan scam involving Mumbai-based Money Matters Financial Services.         
	Money Matters allegedly bribed senior officials of public sector banks and financial institutions to give loans to corporate houses, mostly real estate developers and builders.         
	Apart from Nair, others arrested were Naresh Chopra, investment secretary of the Life Insurance Corporation, M.S. Johar, director (chartered accountant) of the Central Bank of India, R.N. Tayal, general manager of the Bank of India, Venkoba Gujjal, deputy general manager of Punjab National Bank (Delhi), Rajesh Sharma, chairman and managing director of Money Matters, and two officials of the firm.         
	According to the CBI, which has been pressing for extending the custody of the accused till December 3, Nair received a total of Rs 45 lakh for clearing projects worth Rs 470 crore of the three developers.                                                                                                                                       
